Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button + confirmation dialog:**

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    public EditProductPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();

        // Replace back arrow with "Cancel" button
        Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
        {
            TextOverride = "Cancel",
            Command = new Command(async () => await TryNavigateBack())
        });
    }

    // Also intercept hardware/gesture back
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () => await TryNavigateBack());
            return true; // cancel default navigation
        }
        return false; // allow default navigation
    }

    private async Task TryNavigateBack()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!leave)
                return; // cancel navigation
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- `Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior` — customizes the button text and overrides its tap action.
- `OnBackButtonPressed()` — intercepts Android hardware back and swipe-back gestures. Return `true` to cancel navigation.
- The `Command` on `BackButtonBehavior` handles the shell toolbar button tap.

**2. Track unsaved changes** by setting `_hasUnsavedChanges = true` whenever a form field changes (e.g., via `TextChanged` events or property-changed notifications in your view model).

> **Note:** iOS swipe-back gesture isn't fully interceptable by `OnBackButtonPressed` in all MAUI versions. Setting `BackButtonBehavior.Command` disables the default back navigation (including the swipe gesture on iOS in Shell), which ensures your confirmation logic always runs.
